	I seriously doubt that a pentacle, qua pentacle (it's a mullet,
remember) would have gotten a Herald or a Churchman in 1200 at all
exercised.  It wasn't a symbol of anything in particular until _much_
later -- I would guess the 1600s.

	Thor hammers (Mjollnir), stag's heads, boar's heads, etc., are
pretty common, and they were clan/tribal totems from pagan times (and
still are, among the German Jaeger societies -- but that's another
story).

	The pentacle as a general symbol of paganism is strictly
post-Gardnerian (i.e. after 1950), and, as far as I can tell, the
reversed pentacle with a goat's head is Victorian -- Eliphas Levi, et
al., though it _may_ go back to the mid-1600s (diabolism & balck masses
in the Court of Louis XIV in France).

	Faced with a large, hairy, and possibly violent "nobleman" in
