Greetings to Master Sam'l Bassett, from Lord Arval Benicoeur.

> 	Faced with a large, hairy, and possibly violent "nobleman" in
> 1200, saying "I wan _dat_ _ting_ on mah shield!!!", the average Herald is
> going to have said: "Yes, your Grace!!!"  At most he would have said:
> "But yr Grace, Count Bloodspatter of Runningore, two valleys over, is
> using that, and a noble like yourself wouldn't want to be mistaken for
> _HIM_, would you???"

The argument here, that in period the heralds didn't tell the nobles
what to do, is a difficult one to refute.  However, historical
evidence certainly points to the contrary.  Heraldry was born in the
late 12th century, and spread throughout France and western Germany
remarkably fast: 50 years after the first surviving evidence of
heraldic usage (stained glass of Geoffrey of Anjou), there are
hundreds of examples of heraldry throughout the area of modern France,
Belgium, and Holland.  Furthermore, the range of charges used was
motably small: The standard ordinaries, the lion, and the eagle
account for the great majority of all early heraldic insignia.
Indeed, this limited range lasted well into the medieval period.  An
ordinary of pre-1400 rolls of arms shows very few odd charges.  Most
of the unusual charges found were certainly adopted for canting
purposes.

The conclusion is either that nobles DID let the heralds tell them
what was supposed to be in heraldry, or that social convention
dictated that certain things were acceptable and others were not.
Arms were adopted by nobles because they were the new, stylish, and
accepted symbol of nobility: A lord had arms, and his arms were the
evidence that he was noble (and were often accepted as such without
further support!)  To adopt odd armory, out of the prevailing style,
would be to exclude the bearer from the noble clique defined by
armory, which is certainly a goal no noble would pursue.

	Arval.
