Greetings from Arval.

His Grace Duke Cariadoc asks, of SCA, Inc. membership:

> But why should people be required to send tribute? Why (in the context of
> local events with discounts for members, which is a different version of
> the same idea) should I, after spending the day in the kitchen cooking the
> feast, be told that I was working to increase the amount of tribute that
> went to the West? If people do not value TI and their local newsletter
> enough want to pay the price, why should we pressure them to join anyway?
> Pennsic exists for a variety of good purposes, but I do not think that
> increasing the revenue of the SCA Inc. is one of them--indeed, I am not
> even sure it is a good purpose.

I find several reasons to encourage, or even require membership for
certain forms of participation in the Society.  None of these ideas
are original, but it seems worth putting them all down in one place.

As has oft been noted, the SCA is almost unique in that it does not
require membership, or anything else beyond an attempt to dress
medieval, for participation in its events.  This fact is not a reason
to require membership, but it does suggest that older, established
groups have found it a beneficial requirement.

The reasons are practical.  There are certain expenses associated with
running the SCA, both on the national and local level.  Insurance,
legal representation, office expenses, and the like are necessary, and
have to come from somewhere.  The larger the organization, the higher
these costs rise.  We need insurance, for example, to cover everyone
who participates in an SCA event, not just members.  Is it fair to
extend these services to people unwilling to make a minimal monetary
commitment to the organization?  One can cite similar expenses closer
to the medieval activity of the SCA: Running the SCA marshallate, and
publishing rules of the lists; Running BoD meetings; Running the SCA
Chirurgeonate.  Each of these bodies serves everyone who attends SCA
events, and each has to be supported by SCA membership fees.

On a more philosophical level, there is the argument that membership
demonstrates a basic commitment to the SCA.  Running Pennsic War, to
address the original topic of this discussion, is an enormous amount
of work.  I help do it because I enjoy it, but I would enjoy it just
as much if the War were smaller, and I would find it much more
satisfying if I knew that everyone for whose benefit I scream my lungs
out year after year was a real SCA member, not just a summer weekend
groupie.  Why should I (and the several hundred other folk who help
run the War) expend all this effort for someone who doesn't even care
enough to find $6.00 (or $20, for that matter) per year to support the
SCA?  

SCA dues are not "tribute to the West", and I strongly recommend that
we avoid that idea; they are payment to help run the organization.
Membership requirements are not intended to increase the income of the
corporation; they are meant to discourage people who are not really
interested in the SCA, and who make work, expense, and trouble for
those of us who are.  Personally, I cannot understand how anyone can
actively participate in the SCA without maintaining membership: It is
discourteous, if nothing else.

	Arval.
