/* ---------- "Minors at Pennsic, Membership requi" ---------- */
"If you are under 18 and are injured, no matter where you are in America,
you can NOT be treated for ANYTHING until your legal guardians/parents
give the ok." (Cynthia du Pre Argent)

"The problem is largely that in Pennsylvania (and many Eastern states)
medical care *cannot* be given to a minor without the express written (and
specific) consent of his/her legal parents or guardians. Many states have
a provision for the appointment of a temporary guardian, and it is simpler
in some places than others. In some states, a simple notarized letter
would do..." (Li Kung Lo)

"However, I am a parent, of four children, and we live in Pennsylvania.
This year all four of them will be at camp without us. ... For all of them
we sign a form giving permission for emergency medical care as needed,
before they ever go.... And yes, our children have been treated, more than
once, without our prior explicit permission beyond what's on the
form."(Paula Matuszek)

"The difference, my lady, is that commercial organizations like the Boy
Scouts and summer camps, and government organizations like schools have
access to insurance that the SCA and the Coopers simply cannot afford. 
Pennsic War is held at a private camp ground.  It isn't a Boy Scout camp
or a commercial summer camp, and the owners do not have insurance to cover
unsupervised children.  Their insurance company has told them that they
must ban children without parents, pets, and other insurance risks. 
Furthermore, to be fair, even if the Coopers could get that kind of
insurance, there is no good reason for them to pay for it." (Arval).

I am quoting from all of these postings because they illustrate a very
common pattern in SCA discussions (and elsewhere). The sequence starts
with a confident, authoritative statement, which seems to settle the
matter: "no matter where you are in America, you can NOT be treated for
ANYTHING." It turns out from the second, and considerably more detailed
statement, that the first is false--or at least Li Kung Lo, who sounds
rather better informed than the previous poster, says that it is ("In some
states, a simple notarized letter would do..."). 

We then get evidence that seems to clearly contradict both statements--if
"medical care *cannot* be given to a minor without the express written
(and specific) consent of his/her legal parents or guardians (Li Kung Lo)"
then it cannot be given to a minor attending a summer camp or a boy scout
camp, both private organizations with the same legal rights as the
Coopers. If, as Paula Matuszek says (and she is the first participant in
the discussion to offer evidence instead of assertion), her children were
so treated, then both Cynthia du Pre Argent and Li Kung Lo are wrong--or
at least are seriously overstating the real situation.

Finally, we get a new assertion by Arval, equally authoritative, equally
confident that he is right, and again without evidence.

Summer camps as I remember them have a few hundred kids and are open from
one to two months. Pennsic runs about a week, and must average about
3000-4000 people during that week. It is by no means obvious which is the
bigger enterprise, hence not obvious that, in Arval's words, "summer camps
.. have access to insurance that the SCA and the Coopers simply cannot
afford."

My point here is not that the rule against minors is wrong. I simply do
not know enough about either the legal situation or the costs of different
kinds of insurance to say whether version three of the
"absolutely-confident-how could-anyone-but-an-idiot-disagree" explanation
of why minors without their parents are not permitted at Pennsic is
actually a reasonable defense. Neither, so far as I can tell, does anyone
who has yet contributed to the argument.

I have spent so much space on this question because it is something that
appears again and again--authoritative statements about why we have to do
something in a particular way, frequently statements about the law by
non-lawyers, accompanied by no evidence and often wrong. When the issue
was women fighting, the assertion was that we would be in violation of
civil rights law unless we permitted it. I checked that twice with
competent professionals, who both assured me that there was no truth to
it. When TYC was being organized, it was announced that selling food on
site (by SCA people) would not be permitted. I tried to see if something
could be done about that, in the hope that we could get something like the
old Sated Tyger (period food, produced and sold on a large scale). I was
told, by one of the organizers, that it was absolutely impossible because
of peculiarities of Texas law, and (in print, in the TYC newsletter) that
my suggestion that the real reason might be that the proprietor of the
site wanted to keep the business for his concessionaires was paranoid. I
arrived at TYC to find that there was one group of SCA people who were
making and selling food. I asked them about it, and was told that it was
all right because what they sold did not compete with what the
concessionaires sold!

My general conclusion is that, unless you know your source to be reliable,
you should give very little credence to assertions on such matters (or on
other matters, such as questions of authenticity), and less weight the
more confidently they are made. One should be particularly skeptical of
versions of "we are only doing this because someone else makes us." They
may be true, but they should not be taken on faith. 

On to another subject.

"Running Pennsic War, to address the original topic of this discussion, is
an enormous amount of work. ... Why should I (and the several hundred
other folk who help run the War) expend all this effort for someone who
doesn't even care enough to find $6.00 (or $20, for that matter) per year
to support the SCA?"

While I appreciate Arval's feeling, I have a problem with his logic. He
seems to be assuming his conclusion--that paying for a membership is the
proper test of whether you "care enough." One of our local people was not
a member at the point when he "cared enough" to autocrat a crown tourney.
Later, at a point when he was a member but his lady was not, he cared
enough to offer that, if our free event cost us more than we had in our
treasury, he would make up the difference (he is employed but not rich).
Following Arval's logic, shall I conclude that anyone who cares less than
this gentleman should be banned from Pennsic? That he is "not really
interested in the SCA, and ... make(s) work, expense, and trouble for
those of us who are."?

Arval has a better point when he argues that part of the membership goes
for things, such as insurance, that benefit all participants, whether or
not they are members, and that it is therefore both fair and reasonable to
pressure participants to be members. This immediately raises the question
of how much of the membership goes for insurance. If the answer is close
to six dollars, Arval has a reasonable argument; if it is close to fifty
cents, he does not. Does he know which it is? I don't.

Of course, Arval wants to include, in addition to insurance, a lot of
administrative overhead. That is the point at which we may disagree about
whether we are buying a good or a bad. While the central organization
undoubtedly does some useful things, I believe it also has substantial
undesirable effects. One (very period) way of minimizing them is to keep
it poor--by requiring that it, like the rest of the organization, run on
volunteer labor and a shoestring. This could become a long argument, so I
will save examples and further points for a later round.

There is a second issue that the question of participants getting a free
ride on members raises. The Society survives and prospers, in large part,
because many of us do things from which others benefit. Arval's work at
Pennsic is a good example--and one not paid for from memberships. I could
list quite a lot of others. The Society is run on donated volunteer labor,
not cash--our feasts are not cooked, our clothes are not made, our poems
are not written, by people hired with money from memberships. I think it
entirely reasonable that people who have been in for some time and do not
contribute to the Society should be treated with less regard than those
who do--and, as a rule, they are. I simply do not see that membership has
much to do with contribution.


David Friedman (Cariadoc)
College of Grey Gargoyles, Middle Kingdom
Chicago, IL

