	Current rules are:

AR1. 	Rule of Contrast.  Dark tinctures shall not be placed upon dark 
	tinctures nor light tinctures upon light.  Color-fielded ermine
	furs may be combined with other dark tinctures where contrast is
	maintained.  Proper charges must always have sufficient contrast.

	a. Definitions. Dark tinctures are colors (e.g.,sable), color-fielded
	ermine furs (e.g.,azure ermined Or), and dark proper (e.g., wood 
	proper).  Light tinctures are metals (e.g.,Or), metal-fielded furs
	(e.g., ermine), and pale proper (e.g.,stone proper).  Neutral tinctures
	are multiply divided fields of light and dark tinctures (e.g., lozengy
	gules and argent), vair furs (e.g.,vair), and even mixes of light and
	dark proper (e.g.,a zebra proper).  Fields with treatments (e.g., 
	argent masoned sable) are the same as the underlying field.
	b. Scope. The Rule of Contrast applies to all heraldic submissions
	(devices, badges, mon, etc.) and to all charges on those submissions
	(including chiefs, bordures, flaunches, labels, augmentations, marks
	of cadency, etc.) even though this is contrary to mundane practice in
	some systems of heraldry.
	c. Neutral Contrast. Neutral tinctures may be used with any metal,
	color, or fur except either of the component tinctures.  They may be
	used with the component tinctures only in simple cases.
	d. Contrast with Ermine Furs. Certain ermine-based furs with color
	fields have been specifically ruled to have sufficient contrast with
	some colors.  A color charge may be placed on a color field it at least
	one of the colors has a pattern of metal ermine spots, and the colors
	are chosen from following combinations: gules +{sable,vert,azure},
	sable+{gules,vert).  

AR2.	Rules of Party Fields and Charges.
	a. Combination Limit. Fields or charges parted with one of the 
	following lines of division may be tinctured as any combination
	of light, dark, and neutral tinctures: Per pale, Per fess, Per bend
	(sinister), Per chevron (inverted), Per pall (inverted), Quarterly,
	Per saltire.  Except for gyronny (noted below), all other divided
	fields shall not use combinations drawn solely from the same class
	of tincture. 
	b. Gyronny. Gyronny of 6 or 8 may be only light + dark, neutral +
	{light,dark}, or composed of a sufficient-contrast combination, 
	which is to say, gules+{sable, vert, azure}, sable + {gules,vert}.
	Gyronny from the edge of the field, and gyronny of more than eight
	shall obey the combination limit for divided fields.
	c. Partition Lines. In simple cases only, a party field tinctured
	either all dark or all light may use a complex line of partition.


(all typoes mine, I hope there aren't too many...)


	So there is no reason for the above combination of Per pall
metal, color, color, and I suspect that it (or a close cousin) is in
use somewhere in the SCA.  As for gyronny of 5 and 7 and 9...  other than
that it is easier to divide a field up into even numbered parts I don't
see why not...  (except that you'd probably contrast, at 7 and 9, with 
simular tinctures of 6, 8 and 10.)  Gyronny of five might even make
for a distinctive device...

