The following comments are, to the best of my recollection, the current
rules on tinctures in the SCA.  Mundane heraldry may be different;
and I haven't got my Heralds Handbook in my office, so I can't double-
check my memories.

There are three classes of tincture, light (the metals "Or" and "argent"),
medium (the furs, such as "vair"), and dark (the colors "purpure", "sable", 
"gules", "vert", and "azure"). (** Please no flames about vert and purpure! **)
I believe that the mostly-light furs, such as "ermine" are counted as light,
and the mostly-dark ones, such as "counter-ermine" are counted as good
 -- oops -- I mean dark.  Charges blazoned as "proper" are assumed to
fall into one of these categories, i.e., an "oar proper" is dark, and
a "sword proper" is light.

Furs can be used anywhere any ticture can be, as long as the rules
of tincture are obeyed, i.e., no charge shall be placed on a charge or
field of the same class (dark on dark, etc.).  The exact policy has
a few loopholes, which I don't remember because the Western CoH
has unilateraly closed them.

Divided fields complicate matters.  For two-way divided fields, at least,
all color-combinations are permitted, but low-contrast divided fields
are discriminated against when it comes to counting points of difference:
the difference between "per pale vert and sable" and "per pale vert and
argent" is less than the difference between "per pale vert and argent" and 
and "per pale vert and or".  (I hope I got that right.)

Charges on divided fields need, at the least, good contrast on the
identifying features of the charge.  I won't say more 'til I have
the rules in front of me.

I hope you have found this helpful.
 
