this fine institution to attend to the needs of their machines. This 
employment has its advantages, among them this forum. I have been 
reading these proceedings for a few weeks while I have been learning the 
system here, and I am now confident that I am able to manipulate the 
editor in a satisfactory manner. To those persons among you which it is my 
pleasure to have met: Hello! And to those whom I have yet to meet in 
person: also, hello!
	       On to my thoughts:
1. To Cyrus Hammerhand.
     Since my only two available modes of transpotation are by hoof and 
motercycle, I frequently play in traffic on two wheels and in armor. In 
Wisconsin, helmets are required only for those riders under the age of 
18. I would never wear my fighting helm while riding for the following 
reasons; 1. Riding requires eye protection, and my helmet protects 
against only those missles smaller than 1", 2. Motorcycle helmets are 
made so that the rider can be tossed on his head without injury, SCA 
helms are fashioned so that a blow with a weapon causes no damage. The 
additional mass and protuberences of my helmet would make a crash more 
dangerous, and 3. I get enough weird looks from the local gendarmerie as 
it is in my armor without inviting additional inspection. However, I 
consider my armor even better body protection than my leathers. In 
closing on this subject >>>ALWAYS WEAR YOUR HELMET WHEN RIDING<<<. 
(Fighters should find this intuitively obvious.)
     2. Computer heraldry. 
     Many years ago, I designed a program for just such those purposes 
as have been described, but I gave up the project in frustration at the 
micros of that era. Now I think that they might just be powerful enough 
to handle this task. I'll put it in line with my other projects. I 
believe the design is still valid.
     3. Minors at Pennsic.       
     When I joined the SCA, I was a minor whose parents had no interest. 
I had more problems with being accepted as a person (by some, not many) 
than I ever did with official sanctions. I have been to many Pennsics, 
and I have seen minors both good and bad, accompanied and unaccompanied. 
My personal opinion is that some supervision is necessary, but only 
allowing minors present with their parents present may be a bit much.
     4. Baronial Stuff.
     In Jaravellir, we have a Baroness who has reigned for an 
exceedingly long time, and had somewhat lessened her participation in 
the Barony. Certain factions of the populace wanted a figurehead who 
would be more visible to the community. Several ballots and unofficial 
polls were taken, and the result was an election to determine who the
recommended lord wold be. As one of those nominated, I would say that 
the least friction in this case was among those on the ballot. Such was 
the chaos and outcry that when the recommendation was finally sent to 
the Crown, a 'Lieutenant Baron' was announced. This was not an 
acceptable action to those nominated, but was done because of the severe 
objections of some of the members of the Barony. The lord chosen had a 
hard time actually doing anything because he wasn't a *real* Baron, and 
there were those who felt that the appointment was arbitrary. I 
apologize now for any politicking which may come from my home; I am 
sorry that some people must suffer to hear my Barony's dirty laundry.
     5. In Closing.
     I am sorry this is so long, but it is my first article, and I had a 
lot of ground to cover. I look forward to continuing to enjoy your 
electronic company.
