/* ---------- "Anuddah newbie!" ---------- */
Good-day gentlefolk,

After finding this newsgroup yesterday afternoon and spending much of
the ensuing 15 hours catching up on 500+ articles, I find myself being
much more interested in the SCA than I was when I started (which is to
say I wanted to become a member, now I MUST become a member.)  But
first, a few questions:

1.  I am currently living in Worcester, MA (it's the armpit between
Boston and Springfield) and will be here until next May, at least.
Where is the nearest Shire and what can I do to join?  Unfortunately,
I have no form of transportation other than a bicycle and a great
willingness to walk, if needs be.
   a.  Where can I get training in techniques of battle?  I do not own
any armor, or a practice sword (I do have a nice bastard sword), but I
would like to learn more about the blade.  In fact, I'd prefer not to
use armor at all, but safety considerations...
   b.  Where could I get several rattan swords?  I'm handling weaponry
and some weaponplay for a production of _Macbeth_ here at WPI next
November.  I have access to many daggers and swords, but nothing for
practice.

Well, that's it for the questions.  Now for some comments.  One of the
first things I noticed was duct tape.  I hadn't known it had that use.
It's used in theatre commonly under the term "gaffer's tape."  I've
seen it used to tape lights to bars, mark cables, hold costumes
together, and even hold people up, but never taping swords!

Now, for a general compliment: there were/are no flames!!!!
Thank-you, everyone, for being so open and friendly.

Hmmmmm, what else?  Oh, when is Pennsic?  After all those messages,
all I've found is that it's located somewhere in western Pennsylvania
and it occurs in the summer.  I'd really like to go, if things work out.

The whole authenticity thing is tied to beauracracy, I believe, which
ties in the Pennsic 'problems', naming, and just about everything the
SCA is.  A word of warning, from someone who handles paperwork:  keep
the beauracracy to a minimum.  As someone who definitely wants to
join, the membership w/out payment idea is nice, but not necessary.
But for those people who are trying out the SCA, it's really great.
To deny people entrance because they're not members causes a lot of
extra red tape for both the autocrats and the (possibly) new gentles.
The whole business with the names sounds somewhat like the problem
with radio censorship:  when does a submitted name go beyond the SCA
limits of validity?  (Radio stations have the problem with decency)
If the people in charge used a modicum of common sense, which SCAdites
seem to have aplenty, there wouldn't be much of a problem.  It's when
you try to follow the letter of the rules, rather than the spirit,
that things get difficult.

Just my deux centimes,

jon

